<h1 id="WhatIs">What is menosgrande?</h1>
<div class="indent">
  <p>menosgrande is a service for shortening URLs. You give it a long URL, such as</p>
  <pre class="codebox">http://www.google.com/mars/#lat=-14.569960&lon=175.470542&zoom=12&map=infrared&q=spacecraft</pre>
  <p>and menosgrande turns it into a short URL such as</p>
  <pre class="codebox">http://æ.is/뎴</pre>
  <p>This is useful for when one wants to share a long URL, but is limited to a certain number of characters (e.g. the Twitter status update limit is 140 characters).</p>
</div>

<h1 id="HowWork">How does it work?</h1>
<div class="indent">
  <p>When you visit a short URL generated by menosgrande, your browser is transparently given a signal to redirect to a new location (technically an <a href="http://www.w3.org/Protocols/rfc2616/rfc2616-sec10.html#sec10.3.2">HTTP 301</a> response). This signal is SEO/web crawler friendly, so your search engine rankings will not be negatively affected.</p>
</div>

<h1 id="WhyUse">Why should I use menosgrande instead of other URL shorteners?</h1>
<div class="indent">
  <p>menosgrande creates much shorter links than other URL-shortening services by doing a few things intelligently:</p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong><a href="http://unicode.org/standard/WhatIsUnicode.html">Unicode</a> paths</strong> (i.e. <a href="http://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc3987">IRI</a>s). While other URL shortening services use the digits [a-zA-Z0-9] only, resulting in <span style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold;">62</span> unique characters, menosgrande uses <span style="font-style: italic; font-weight: bold;">over 107,000</span> unique Unicode code points. Using a little <a href="http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Combinatorics.html">math</a>, it can be shown that menosgrande can store over twelve times the number of URLs in two Unicode digits than other services using five base-62 digits (<a href="http://www.google.com/search?q=107000^2%2F62^5">compare 107000^2 to 62^5</a> to see the difference).</li>
    <li><strong>Short domains</strong>. Some services use long domain names, which waste characters from the start (e.g. goo.gl, tinyurl.com, etc.). menosgrande uses a <span style="font-style: oblique">two-digit</span> <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Top-level_domain">TLD</a> and a <span style="oblique">single-digit</span> subdomain, resulting in a base URL that is already extremely short - always four digits.</li>
    <li><strong>Multiple domains</strong>. menosgrande doesn't attempt to use a single unique domain name for short links. Instead, it keeps a pool of domains for that purpose. Each domain in this pool multiplies the number of URLs that menosgrande can shorten.</li>
  </ul>
</div>
  
<h1 id="WhatMean">What does 'menosgrande' mean?</h1>
<div class="indent">
  <p><span style="font-style: oblique">Menos grande</span> is a Spanish phrase meaning 'less big'. If you're a fan of anime, you may also recognize it as being <a href="http://bleach.wikia.com/wiki/Hollow#Gillian">a character</a> from a series called <a href="http://bleach.viz.com/">Bleach</a>.</p>
</div>
